<TITLE> UK banks don't object to 2nd term for BoE's King:BBA </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Dec 11 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - British banks have no problem with Bank of England Governor Mervyn King getting a second term as head of the central bank, the British Bankers' Association chief Angela Knight told Reuters on Tuesday. Knight also said there was little reason to suspect that another British bank would follow mortgage lender Northern Rock to the wall despite continuining difficulties in credit markets. "I don't think the banking sector would have a problem," Knight said in an interview when asked what the response would be to King being reappointed when his term expires in June next year. The central bank chief has taken considerable flak in the last few months over the handling of the squeeze in money markets and the Northern Rock banking debacle, which saw the first run on a British bank in 140 years. There have also been calls for BoE Deputy Governor John Gieve to resign, given his responsibility for financial stability, but Knight said the BBA would prefer structures to change rather than go looking for scapegoats. "We don't go for scalps," she
